(Key Ideas To Remember) Tj
T*
(- Statistics should first be understood as a mathematical idea before it is treated as) Tj
T*
(an exam topic.) Tj
T*
(- The learner must understand measures of central tendency, spread, and data) Tj
T*
(representation because it controls how questions in Statistics are answered correctly.) Tj
T*
(- A strong answer in Statistics uses the correct solution method and explains why that) Tj
T*
(method fits the task.) Tj
T*
(- Comparing two data sets using mean and range is the type of application that helps) Tj
T*
(move the topic from explanation to mastery.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Step-By-Step Method) Tj
T*
(1. Read the question or example and identify the part connected to Statistics.) Tj
T*
(2. Recall the specific rule, process, or principle behind measures of central tendency,) Tj
T*
(spread, and data representation.) Tj
T*
(3. Apply the correct solution method step by step instead of jumping to the answer.) Tj
T*
(4. Check the result carefully and confirm that it matches the requirement of the topic.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Worked Examples) Tj
T*
(Worked Example 1) Tj
T*
(1. Start with an example based on comparing two data sets using mean and range.) Tj
T*
(2. Identify the exact idea in measures of central tendency, spread, and data) Tj
T*
(representation that the question is testing.) Tj
T*
(3. Apply the correct method for Statistics step by step without skipping reasoning.) Tj
T*
(4. Check the final answer and explain why it is correct.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Worked Example 2) Tj
T*
(1. Choose a second example that still focuses on reading charts and calculating mean,) Tj
T*
(median, mode, and range.) Tj
T*
(2. Break the task into smaller parts and link each part to the rule being used.) Tj
T*
(3. Point out how to avoid using the wrong average or ignoring outliers while solving it.) Tj
